        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>2. Bryanston St. | <hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>April 10<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <seg type="supplemental">on Monday home</seg>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I have received the M.S all right &amp; am very glad that you will publish it as a separate little book.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I most heartily hope that it may not prove a loss. I know that some persons have been much interested in it, though it has been read by very few.—</p>
<p>Yours very sincerely | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.1 <hi rend="italic">Kent.</hi>] <hi rend="italic">before del</hi> ‘<hi rend="italic">Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi>’ </note>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9921.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from John Murray, 9 April [1875]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Murray had returned the manuscript of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1458.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Climbing plants</hi> 2d ed.</ref>; see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9921.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from John Murray, 9 April [1875]</ref> and n. 2.</note>
